{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_madison_ver01/data/sn95047168/00541310514/1949062401/0196.xml":{"full_text":"Union Conntit Himes\nLEX GREEN Publisher Editor-In-Chief\nBILKER Managing-Editor\nPublished Every Friday at Lake Butler, Florida\n^d as second class mail mat ter April 8, 1921, at the Post,\ne at Lake Butler Flor da under the At of March 3, 1879.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATE\n$2.00 per year\u2014ln Advance\nz member' $1.25 six months\u2014in advance\nFLORIDA PRFGC Advertising Rates Cheerfully\nfurnished at this office\nASSOCI ATION NATIONAL EDITORIAL\nI lIASSOCIATION\nWe Commend Governor Warren\nRecommend Governor Fuller Warren for his offered personal\nLnancial sacrifices towards economy for the tax payers of Florida\nHe recently indicated his willingness and desire to forego im\nmediate pay ment of three months salary in order that the execut\nl'e department budget may be balanced.\nWe hope that cabinet members and all state employees may\ncome forth now and join, the Governor in his determined reduct-\u00a7\nion of spending. The income and the business of the average]\nind.vidual is rapidly declining and, in fact, many believe that we\narc already heading into a most serious financial depression. The}\npuces of many common commodities are nosing downward and,\nin tact have fallen rapidly in the last 12 months. During the\nnext three years many anticipate that prices on practically every\ncommodity will continue to go down until the depths of a most|\nvenous depression may be reached some 3 or 4 years from now.'\nIt all state employees, bureaucrats, cabinet members, budget\nmakers and spenders, would immediately cut their own spending,\nand their own receipts in keeping with that of the individual or;\nbusiness man on theoutside then our state budget would not onlyl\nblanced but there would be healthy balance over on the money\nide of the register.\nWhy, in view of these things, should any individual who is I\ngaining his income from public taxes refuse or decline to make\nthis proporionate cut in salary, wages, or income?\nBy The-Editor-In-Cbief\nAgainst Session Of Legislature\nWe can see no good reason for calling of the Legislature back\nTo ordinary session at this time. The members of the Legisua-}\nlure are the direct representatives of the people. They have re-/\ncently had their statutory 60-day session and there enacted such\nlegislation as was decided by the majority to be proper. They\ndeclined to impose many new and additional taxes which were\ndesired by some. It appears that those who hoped to receive di-\nrect or indirect benefits from additional taxes favored both. It\nappears that those who were not on the money receiving end of\nthe line but who were tp pay the additional taxes and penalities\nopposed, and the latter group won in the recent session.\nThe fact remains that sufficient taxes are already in effect to\nbring into the state treasurer about $186,000,000 for the two-I\nyear periods. This is the amount, approximately, which former\nGovernor Millard Filmore Coldwell, the spender, used to operate\nstate function. With his lavish spending in mony-easy years it\nappears now that with a recession in busiess and a recession in in\ncomes the Florida government could be carried on with this\namount of money or even less.\nIt is true that] certain cabinet members and state bureaucrats j\nalways clamor for and desire more money to spend. They desire\nthese funds in order that they may on reelection years boastl\nabout what great services their respective departments have\nrendered to the public. They desire these monies also to ap-I\npoint more employees and to build up, with state funds, a greaterl\nelection machine with which to perpetuate themselves in office.\nYes, indeed, it is time to call a halt in federal, state .county and\nmunicipal spending. By force of necessity individuals and busi\nr<ses are forced to curb their spending on account of an ever\ndeclining income and declining business. Therefore, let govern\nmental units he governed by the same rules of economy as are\nthe individuals and businesses. Then, we do not desire nor need\nat this time an extraordinary session of the Legislature- with the\nhope of the spenders to gather more money from the public anlj\nspend more, most of it for their selfish designs.\nBy The Editor-In-Chief\nEurope Prospering\nHal Boyle recently wrote an interesting story concerning ex-ist\ng prosperity in Europe. This is not shocking news to us be\nse the I nittd States has been, under the Marshall plan and\ncher wise, spending billions in Europe ever since Hitler's forces\nd lojos forces surrendered. We have never been able to un\nrstand why I ncle Sam should continuously, ever since the war,\n^7 perhaps for many years in the future, play Santa Clause to\nc peoples of Europe, Asia and Africa.\nFrom Mr. Boyle's artical, it appear- that in many instances\nany Europeans and many European countries are better off\n'nan many nations in the Western Hemisphere and indeed better\n4 U* economically Can millions of people in the good old U. S. A.\nEven the Marshall plan has been giving these foreigners for\nyears almost thirteen million dollars daily in American goods and\n\\merican money. It appears that some hidden and unusual in\nerwe over our American government and our American Con\ngre-s is operating in such a manner as to cause our governmental\n-fficmls and our Congressmen and Senators to desire to do more\nforeigners and foreign countries more than they pre willing to\ndo for our own Americans and our own nation. We read recen\nty that our President and his leaders were now planning to, in\nme manner, attempt to stimulate industry, business employment\nthe United States. Yet, these same individuals, many of them\nair still recommending and voting for an expenditure of more\n12 million dollars daily to f and foreign countries,\nmany of whom were our enemies under arms in the recent con\nfi>k. Such philosophy of government cannot and will not add\nup W American security, neither economically nor from a military\npc.nt of view. In the last two world wars. American resources\nand stable goods and money and unreplenished power have been\ncraned to an alarming degree and surely those in power in Wash\nngton should have an awakening as to what will be the future of\nour nation and our people if they do not exercise American\neconomy, American government as such, and indeed and in fact\npreserve, protect and conserve America for Americans.\nBy The-Editor-In-Chief\nUNION COUNTY TIMES, LAKE BUTLER, FLORIDA\n'FARM NEWS\nBy: William J. Cowen,\nCounty Agent\nState Guernsey Club Slates\nField Day at Winter Park July 8.\nThe Florida Guernsey Cattle\nClub will hold a field day here, at\nIthe Lakemont Dairy farm of Car-\nI roid Ward, on July 8. according\nto C. U. Reaves, extension dairy\nman with the University of\n;Florida.\nGuernsey breeders and other\ninterested dairyman from all over\n;the state have been invited to\nI spend the day seeing examples of\nlimproved dairy practices and\nbreeding methods on the Ward\nfarm which Ivas been officially\nclassified for type by an inspector\nlof the American Guernsey Cattle\nClub.\nl According to Reaves, this is the\nI first time the Florida club has\nIheld a meeting on a farm which\nI has been officially typed and it\nwill provide an opportunity for\nbreeders to study the official\nclassification.\nThe home-grown cows on the\nI Lakemont Dairy have made ex-\nIceptionally good production re-\nI cords as shown by DHIA and Ad-\nIvanced Registry records kept in\n:cooperation with the Universityl\nlof Florida.\nlAlso scheduled for the day is a\ncattle judging contest for TH\nIjudging teams from nearby count-I\nCarroll Ward is president of the\nlassociationI association and John H^nry Lo-|\n;gan. Pinallas County Agent is\n;Secretary.\nDDT-Sulphur Dust is Suggested\nTo Check Pea n ut Leafhoppers\nBetter control of the potato\nI leafhopper on peanuts now ap-\nIpears possible through the use of\na DDT-Sulfur dust mixture. This\nIwedge-shopped pale greenish in-\nIsect pest about one-eighth inch\nI long has caused considerable dam\n;age to the peanut crop for many\n;years.\nDr. P. N. Annand, Chief of the/\n;Bureau of Entomology ana Plant/\nQuarantine, USDA, says the DDT-;\nI sulfur dust mixture kills 25 to 30\nIpercent more leafhoppers than\nIdoes sulfur alone. Residues of the\ninsecticide also prevent the vines\n,from quickly becoming reinfested\nIwith leafhoppers. The addition of\nI DDT to the mixture aids in con-\nItrol of many insects injurious to\n'peanuts such as the velvetbeanl\nIcaterpillar and other leaf-feeders..\nDr. Annand said increases con-;\nIsistently average about 25 per-;\nIcent in yields of field-cured nutsl\nas a result of the control of thel\npotato leafhoppers and peanut;\nleaf spot with the DDT-sulfur/\ndust.\nIt was found that a dust con-|\ntaining 1 percent of DDT, 90 per-I\nI cent of sulfur, and 9 percent of a\n.conditioning agent to improve its;\ndusting quality when appliedl\nthree-week intervals beginning,\nabout July 10-15, gave adequate\ncontrol of the potato leafhopper,\nlas well as peanut leaf spot. The\nI first application should be at the\nrate of 15 to 20 pounds per acre.\nI Not more than 80 pounds per acre\nshould be applied in one season|\nACP FUNDS ASSIGNED\nThe $11,400 alloted to Union\nICounty for assistance to farmers\nI of the county in carrying out soil\nand water conservation practices\nunder the 1949 Agricultural Con-|\nservation Program has been as-I\nsigned. Ray Crawford Chair-:\nman of the Union County Agricul\ntural Conservation Committee, ex-I\nplains that when farmers carry'\nout approved conservation pract-\nI ices under program specifications.\nI they will receive financial assist-;\nl ance in defraying the cost.\nUnder the Program a farmer:\nlindicates his intentions to partic-;\npate in the program and lists the\nIconservation practices he intend-/\nto carry out. The amount of\n:assistance he may receive is figur-:\nled according to specific rates for 1\nI each praetce. Then when all the I\nfarmers who intend to cooperate;\nhave submited their plans to the}\nIcounty committee, the total;\namount for practices on the farml\nplans is added up and that total\nladjustedIadjusted to the county allocation.;\nThe County Committee, Mr.\nI Crawford explains, has the re\n,sponsibility of using the funds al\n:located to the county where it\nwill bring the greatest returns in\nIconservation. Approximately\n1243 farmers of Union County\nhave indicated their intentions to\nI cooperate in the program and\ncarry out conservation practices.\nThis compares with 226 for the\nI 1948 program.\nMr Crawford said that assist\n'ance to farmers under the Agri-\nIcultural1cultural Conservation Program\nmakes up about 50 percent of the\nout-of-pocket cost of the practice\nI with the farmers paying the other\nIhalf as well as furnishing laborl\nand transportation,\ni^etefo\u2014tttQ^^\u2014'\nTm from Milwaukee\u2014\nI ought to know... AOI\n^M^^ 4B\nVICTOR McLAGLEN j\nFamous Movie Star\n$.At? ft^.r;co,* ^4.<tt.w.t I\nrar-1\nL__:- <1 mnffifli\nSOUND SIMPLICITY at rock-bottom cost is the keynote of this new model home recently opened\nhv the Montauk Beach Company, Inc., on Long Island, N. Y. Designed after the suggestions of Douglas\nToomey, building consultant for Good Housekeeping magazine, the architect kept expenses down by:\n(1) Elimination of basement; (2) Simple frame and roof; (3) Dry Wall construction; (4) Simplified\nwindows and trim; (5) Use of closets for partitions. Although the house embodies the latest principles\nind advancements in moderate-priced design and construction, it's so simple to build that the toolwise\namateur can do much of the work. The Montauk House lends itself to any seashore terrain and can be\nused for a summer or year round home. It is featured in the June issue of the magazine.\n1\nnorth\nti Garage j#nm\u00a3^7 ras\n%2''CT4)\u00a7l\nI I Bedroom\nLorag! Kitchen n l o\nII 6 Y\u25a0 7*'< 8-6\n.c\u00a3! r [range, I o\nBreezeway\nLiving Room 1 Bath W\nI 164x114- CT A\nBedroom\n10 4) 13-3\nEnter\u25a0\nHere\n4\nSample Ballat\nCITY OF LAKE BUTLER, FLA.\nELECTION JUNE 28, 1949\nI Instructions: Make a cross markj\nI (X) after the names of the}\nIcandidates of your choice.\nFOR MAYOR\nIVote for One:\nI\nIC M. BRYAN\nI FOR MEMBER CITY COUNCIL\nVote for Two:\n\n:E. B, ANDREWS\nD. BESHEARS\nJ. M. MOORE\nICLEATUS WARD\nFor Mayor\nTo The Citizens of Lake Butler,\nI I hereby announce my candid\nlacy for Mayor. If elected, I;\nI promise to serve you to the very\nI best of my ability. I will ap-I\n;preciate your vote.\nSincerely yours.\nC. M. Bryan\nFor Councilman\nTo The Voters of Lake Butler:}\nI take this means of announcing,\nmy candidacy for Councilman,\nsubject to the City Election to be|\nheld June 28th., if elected I\npromise to be fair, impartial and\neconomical, always working for\nthe betterment of our town, and\ncitizens to the very best of myj\nability.\nYour Friend,\nE. B. Andrews.\nFor Councilman\nTo the Voters of Lake Butler.l\nI take this means of announc-I\ning my candidacy for Councilman\nsubject to the City Election to be\nheld June 28th., 1949. If elect-;\nled I promise to be Fair, Loyall\nand impartial in the performance|\nI of my duties.\nJames M. Moore\nFor Councilman\nTo The Voters of Lake Butler:\nI take this meahs of ahnounc\n;ing my candidacy for Councilman,\nsubject to the City election to be\nheld .June 28, If elected. I\npromise to be fair and impartial\u2022\nin the performance of my duty.\nI will sincerely appreciate your\nsupport.\nRespectfully yours,\nCleatus Ward|\nOur Farm\nMachinery ^^ili\nService ^se^^\n...can save you time and money\nHEADQUARTERS Just what is service?\nf or Here's what we try to do:\nford Tractors, Keep every Ford Trac\ntor and every piece of\nports and accessories Dearborn Farm Equip-\nDearbom Farm nt working at top effi\ni .ciency and be Johnny-\nEquipment and parts on-the-spot when some-\nExpert service thing goes wrong.\nForming information Some f our service is\nfree; some costs only for\nthe parts; some requires a\nreasonable labor charge.\nBut you'll find us fair\nwe want to keep on serv\n11IIMI ing you for a long time.\nDIXIE EQUIPMENT, INC.\n1436 WEST MAIN ST SOUTH PHONE 2639\nGAINESVILLE, FLORIDA\nF\u00a9\u00a9D..i tita^life\nj tf| ANCIENT GREEKS\n,INAUGURATED LarE\ne^/v/ng DINNERS,\n&K2t OFTHE WORLD\n^EBOSTON TE^A PARTY\n(7 773)TUADE COLON\nz^rs ^^op coeeee, u\nWHICH ROSE TO the 3\nTHEN UNHEARD\nOFPRICEOF 7\nT-WENPy CENTS t^J\\\n^R round/ J\nMERRIE OLDE ENG\nLAND'S FAVORITE\nPANCAKE SAUCE\n-H//S 7 BEER\nAAA/XED WITH\nBROWN sugar.\nDYING, WHILE DINING A T N\nIN BED, THEHUNDRED- %%%&7\"&^\\\nYEAR-OLD SISTER OF\nFAMOUS GOURMET\ns^/LL 7 4T-f/E/R//v, /a/\nRUSHED HER SER\nVANTFOR THE\nCopy,,gH /9*9^.1/.C^He\nFRIDAY, JUNE 24, 1949","height":"24429","width":"17508"}}
